>>8565793
>tried to turn booking into a reality TV style shoot gameshow between players
Point matches were supposed to be a regular big thing as seen on their brochures, but they backed off on it and the decision doesn't even get video coverage anymore. They also stopped letting fans vote on the cards after Step6 or so and by the time ARG comes off hiatus it will have been gone for a year. Whatever ideas they were trying out did not really stay for all of 2022 and it's probably a good thing because the various approaches they were trying were ambitious but not meant for
1) the wrestling demographic that they partly alienated with their sweeping changes to format, though they were not attending the shows to begin with since that's the whole reason AWG fell apart. They were not pulling in idol fans because the people they hired were already failed idols or too obscure to have their respective fanbases fill Shinkiba.
2) a steadily expanding roster primarily consisting of green shitters who may leave at a moment's notice for some other talent job, who are working in a competitive environment dealing with popularity contest shit
3) or the whole inherently scripted nature of pro wrestling. You can't present the match results first and then build a match around it while still keeping people interested in what leads to those results.

Finally, after 10 months of doing a TJPW-esque isolation bubble where they didn't have outside guests nor send people elsewhere on a regular basis, that too appears to have changed. We have a few different AWG names taking bookings since at least late November, though I can't rule out all of it was supposed to be for the IR relationship that at this point appears to be dead before it got going. Step1 showed they were trying to pull away from the pro wrestling thing but ended up coming back to it for reasons only management will know.

>Played Sega with my best friend over the weekend, had a weird conversation about which wrestler would be which console. Snowballed into a pretty fun game. Curious what you guys will come up with here some starters we came up with:

>Ric Flair=Atari 2600
Popular in the age of wood-grain, might not look like much today but beloved by a generation, had porn games/flashed people.
>NES=Randy Savage
Arguably a perfect wrestler/console, beloved by just about everyone, fits of paranoia with Elizabeth/Tengen. All the swagger and technical power in the world. Got lost in the 1990s, but was still based.
>Hulk Hogan=Game Boy
More technically limited than the NES, but still beloved by everyone and arguably more popular. Short matches/battery life, still cool despite limitations.
>Kevin Nash=Virtual Boy
Long legs, kekwab of the decade contender, impressive at first glance, good ties to a strong corporation.
>Rick Rude=The TurboGrafx-16
All the potential in the world, plenty of classics, life was cut-short, often forgotten in GOAT discussions.
>Bret Hart=Sega Genesis
A little limited in presentation, technically gifted, has a massive cult following, not afraid of blood but not a full on edge lord, weird relationship with WWE/Nintendo. Good memories from both normies and patricians.
>HBK=SNES
Arguably the GOAT, beloved by critics and normies alike, mortal enemies with SEGA despite reconciliation. Technologically gifted and flashy, pissed off a lot of people for back-stage politics/censorship.
